SIMPLE: indignation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indignation
<hw>In`dig*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>indignation</ets>, L. <ets>indignatio</ets>. See
<er>Indign</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The feeling excited by that which is unworthy, base,
or disgraceful; anger mingled with contempt, disgust, or
abhorrence.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Indignation</qex> expresses a strong and elevated
disapprobation of mind, which is also inspired by something flagitious
in the conduct of another.</q> <rj><qau>Cogan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Haman saw Mordecai in the king's gate, that he stood not up,
nor moved for him, he was full of <qex>indignation</qex> against
Mordecai.</q> <rj><qau>Esther v. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The effect of anger; punishment.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hide thyself . . . until the <qex>indignation</qex> be
overpast.</q> <rj><qau>Is. xxvi. 20.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Anger; ire wrath; fury; rage. See
<er>Anger</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indignify</ent>⟦br⟧
